For all the calculations, we use spin-polarized density functional theory DFT + U methods [64, 65] within the supercell approach that employs periodic boundary conditions (PBC) and plane-wave (PW) basis sets, as implemented in Quantum Espresso [66]. We use the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) for the exchange–correlation density functional as proposed by Perdew, Burke and Ernzerhof (PBE), plus an effective Ueff = 3.3 eV parameter for d electrons of Ti atoms [67–69]. The projector-augmented wave (PAW) potentials are taken from QE repository [70, 71] and the wave functions (augmented charge density) are expanded in plane waves with a 70 (280) Ry cutoff. We apply the surface-slab approach to build up the structural models for (101), (100) and (001) surfaces by cleaving up the optimized bulk structure along those lattice planes and then introducing a 15 Å vacuum slab along the c direction [72]. Our surface models consist of 10-layer slabs containing 40 formula units (120 atoms) (Figure S1 and Table S1). We use the 2 × 2 × 1 k-point sampling based on a Monkhorst–Pack scheme and take into account dipole correction as implemented in QE [73]. The external electric field in the direction perpendicular to the slabs is simulated by adding a sawtooth-like potential to the bare ionic potential [57, 59, 74]. We reverse the slope of the sawtooth potential (F→\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
