				\begin{document}$$\left|\overrightarrow{F}\right|$$\end{document} = − 5 × 10−3, 0, 5 × 10−3 Ha (1Ha = 51.4 V/Å). For Na+ adsorption, we also consider electric field with F→\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left|\overrightarrow{F}\right|$$\end{document}= − 2.5 × 10−3, 2.5 × 10−3 Ha (Figure S2). All the geometry optimizations consist of full atomic-position relaxation for all the layers in the slab until forces on the ions are below 1 × 10−3 a.u. (∼ 0.05 eV/Å). For the electronic convergence, we use a mixing factor for self-consistency of 0.4 and the default Davidson iterative diagonalization with overlap matrix. The convergence threshold on total energy is set to 10–6 a.u..
